{"title_page": "Monstress (comics)", "text_new": "{{short description|Comics series by Marjorie Liu and Sana Takeda}}\n{{Infobox comic book title <!--Wikipedia:WikiProject Comics-->\n|title           = Monstress\n|image           = Monstress-01.png\n|caption         = ''Monstress'' #1 cover\n|schedule        = \n|ongoing=y\n|publisher       = [[Image Comics]]\n|date            = November 2015 \u2013 present\n|issues          = 26\n|genre           = Epic Fantasy\n|main_char_team  = Maika Halfwolf <br>Kippa<br>Master Ren<br>The Monster<br>Corvin D'Oro\n|writers         = [[Marjorie Liu]]\n|artists         = [[Sana Takeda]]\n|pencillers      = \n|inkers          = \n|letterers       = Rus Wooton\n|editors         = Jennifer M. Smith\n|creators        = [[Marjorie Liu]] & [[Sana Takeda]]\n|subcat          = Image Comics\n|sort            = Monstress (comic book)\n|TPB1            = '1.''' ''Awakening\n|ISBN1           = 9781632157096\n|TPB2            = '2.''' ''The Blood\n|ISBN2           = 9781534300415\n|TPB3            = '3.''' ''Haven\n|ISBN3           = 9781534306912\n|TPB4            = '4.''' ''The Chosen\n|ISBN4           = 9781534313361\n}}\n'''''Monstress''''' is an [[epic fantasy]] comics series written by [[Marjorie Liu]] and drawn by [[Sana Takeda]], published since 2015 by the American publisher [[Image Comics]].\n\nThe comic was described by the [[Los Angeles Review of Books]] as \"ambitious as [[George R. R. Martin]] or [[J. R. R. Tolkien]]\" for its high fantasy concepts and heavy world-building.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lareviewofbooks.org/article/monsters-come-home-marjorie-liu-sana-takedas-monstress/|title=Monsters Come Home: On Marjorie Liu and Sana Takeda\u2019s \u201cMonstress\u201d|last=Song|first=Min Hyoung|website=Los Angeles Review of Books|access-date=2019-05-13}}</ref> The series has earned many awards, including five [[Eisner Award|Eisner Awards]], four [[Hugo Award|Hugo Awards]], and the [[List of Harvey Award winners|Harvey Awards]] Book of the Year in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/newsbrief/index.html?record=2036|title=Publisher's Weekly|last=|first=|date=|website=www.publishersweekly.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref>\n\n== Summary ==\nThe series is set in a [[matriarchal]] world inspired by early 20th century Asia, and tells the story of Maika Halfwolf, a teenage girl who shares a mysterious psychic link with a powerful monster.<ref>{{cite web |title=Marjorie Liu |last1=Liu|first1=Marjorie|url=http://marjoriemliu.com/|accessdate=25 January 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Cruz\">{{cite news|last1=Cruz|first1=Lenika|title=Marjorie Liu on the Road to Making 'Monstress'|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2017/09/marjorie-liu-monstress-interview/539394/|accessdate=25 January 2018|work=The Atlantic}}</ref> The background to the story is a war between the Arcanics, magical creatures who sometimes can pass for human, and the Cumaea, an order of sorceresses who consume Arcanics to fuel their power. Maika is an Arcanic who looks human, and who is set on learning about and avenging her dead mother. Maika's left arm has been severed and a demon occasionally emerges from its stub.<ref name=\"JT\">{{cite news|last1=Kelts|first1=Roland|title=Breaking the comic book glass ceiling|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/culture/2017/03/18/general/breaking-comic-book-glass-ceiling/#.WmoQLLBG1aS|accessdate=25 January 2018|work=The Japan Times|date=19 March 2017}}[http://www.sanatakeda.com/17361773_10155153431077053_2235665766323301491_n.jpg image]</ref> The demon, who takes over her body and mind, is a source of great power, but challenging for Maika to understand and control.<ref name=\"Cruz\" /> \n\nLiu first introduced the story to Takeda in 2013. The two started working together a year later, and the first issue was published in November 2015; the trade paperback first volume in July 2016, the second in July 2017,<ref name=JT/> the third in September 2018,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://imagecomics.com/comics/releases/monstress-vol-3-tp|title=Monstress, Vol. 3 TP|website=Image Comics|language=en|access-date=2019-05-08}}</ref> and the fourth in September 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://imagecomics.com/comics/releases/monstress-vol-4-tp|title=Monstress, Vol. 4 TP|website=Image Comics|language=en|access-date=2019-11-20}}</ref>\n\n== Publication history ==\n[[Marjorie Liu|Liu]] has said that she struggled with depression before writing ''Monstress''. She had taken a hiatus from writing before returning to the industry with Image Comics.<ref name=TheAtlantic>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2017/09/marjorie-liu-monstress-interview/539394/|title=Marjorie Liu on the Road to Making 'Monstress'|last=Cruz|first=Lenika|date=2017-09-14|website=The Atlantic|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-13}}</ref>\n\nShe has described the comic as \"a huge epic fantasy.\" As such, the story required world-building. The first issue was triple-sized (70 pages) in order to properly introduce the various characters and factions.<ref name=TheAtlantic/>\n\nLiu and Takeda first worked together on Liu's run of ''[[X-23]]'' for [[Marvel Comics|Marvel]]. Liu would later describe her work with Takeda as \"a wonderful process; it felt like she was reading my mind.\" A native of Japan, Takeda's art takes inspiration from [[manga]].<ref name=TheAtlantic/>\n\n== Themes ==\n[[File:5.30.19MarjorieLiuByLuigiNovi51.jpg|thumb|left|Liu at a 2019 signing for ''Monstress'' #24 at [[Midtown Comics]] in Manhattan]]\nAccording to Liu, among the series's themes are the inner strength required to withstand constant dehumanization, as well as the power of friendship among women.<ref name=HollywoodReporter>{{cite news|last1=McMillan|first1=Graeme|title='Monstress': Inside The Fantasy Comic About Race, Feminism And The Monster Within|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/monstress-inside-fantasy-comic-race-836391|accessdate=24 November 2015|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=3 November 2015}}</ref> Race also plays a large role in the series. In the series the Arcanics, a race of magical creatures, have been at war with humans for decades, and they are now at a stalemate; however the humans are taking Arcanics and selling them as slaves to other humans.<ref name=HollywoodReporter/>\n\n== Reception ==\nThe first, triple-sized issue of ''Monstress'' received critical praise. Writing for ''[[Kotaku]]'', Evan Narcisse called it \"a gorgeous comic book about racism, war and slavery\", noting the intricate detail of Takeda's [[manga]]-inspired art.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Narcisse|first1=Evan|title=Monstress Is A Gorgeous Comic Book About Racism, War and Slavery|url=http://kotaku.com/monstress-is-a-gorgeous-comic-book-about-racism-war-an-1744178284|accessdate=24 November 2015|work=Kotaku|date=23 November 2015}}</ref> Reviewing the book for [[The A.V. Club]], Caitlin Rosberg described the leading characters, all women, as \"deeply flawed and showing layers of nuanced characterization that you don\u2019t often see in comic books\", and appreciated the series's \"sense of in-between-ness\u2014(...) neither traditionally Western nor manga, paced like a novel but drawn like a comic\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rosberg|first1=Caitlin|title=Monstress captivates with its fusion of Western comics and manga|url=http://www.avclub.com/article/monstress-captivates-its-fusion-western-comics-and-227787|accessdate=24 November 2015|work=A.V. Club|date=10 November 2015}}</ref>{{-}}\n\n===Awards===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n!Award\n!Year\n!Category\n!Nominee\n!Result\n|-\n|rowspan=3|[[British Fantasy Award]]\n|2017<ref name=\"BFA 2017\">{{cite web|title=Announcing the 2017 British Fantasy Award Winners|url=https://www.tor.com/2017/10/01/announcing-the-2017-british-fantasy-award-winners/|website=Tor|accessdate=April 29, 2018}}</ref>\n|Best Comic / Graphic Novel\n|''Monstress \u2013 Volume 1: Awakening''\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2018<ref name=\"BFA 2018\">{{cite web|title=British Fantasy Society, British Fantasy Awards 2018|url=http://www.britishfantasysociety.org/news/british-fantasy-society-british-fantasy-award-2018/|website=[[British Fantasy Society]]|accessdate=November 25, 2018}}</ref>\n|Best Comic / Graphic Novel\n|''Monstress \u2013 Volume 2: The Blood''\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|Best Artist\n|Sana Takeda\n|{{Nominated}}\n|-\n|rowspan=10|[[Eisner Awards]]\n|rowspan=2|2016<ref name=\"Eisners 2016\">{{cite web|title=2016 Eisner Award Winners (Full List)|url=https://www.newsarama.com/30298-2016-eisner-award-winners-full-list.html|website=Newsarama|accessdate=April 29, 2018}}</ref>\n|Best Writer\n|Marjorie Liu\n|{{Nominated}}\n|-\n|Best New Series\n|''Monstress''\n|{{Nominated}}\n|-\n|rowspan=3|2017<ref name=\"Eisners 2017\">{{cite web|title=2017 Eisner Awards Winners (Full List)|url=https://www.newsarama.com/35554-2017-eisner-award-winners-full-list.html|website=Newsarama|accessdate=April 29, 2018}}</ref>\n|Best Publication for Teens (ages 13\u201317)\n|''Monstress''\n|{{Nominated}}\n|-\n|Best Painter/Multimedia Artist (interior art)\n|Sana Takeda\n|{{Nominated}}\n|-\n|Best Cover Artist\n|Sana Takeda\n|{{Nominated}}\n|-\n|rowspan=5|2018<ref name=\"Eisners 2018\">{{cite web|title=2018 Eisner Awards Nominations|url=https://www.newsarama.com/39672-2018-eisner-awards-nominations.html|website=Newsarama|accessdate=April 29, 2018}}</ref>\n|Best Continuing Series\n|''Monstress''\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|Best Publication for Teens (ages 13\u201317)\n|''Monstress''\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|Best Writer\n|Marjorie Liu\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|Best Painter/Multimedia Artist (interior art)\n|Sana Takeda\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|Best Cover Artist\n|Sana Takeda\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|[[Harvey Awards]]\n|2018<ref name=\"Harveys 2018\">{{cite web|title=2018 Winners - The Harvey Awards|url=https://www.harveyawards.com/Winners/2018-Nominees/|website=[[Harvey Awards]]|accessdate=November 25, 2018}}</ref>\n|Book of the Year Award\n|''Monstress''\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|rowspan=4|[[Hugo Awards]]\n|2017<ref name=\"Hugos 2017\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newsarama.com/35915-2017-hugo-awards-winners.html|title=MONSTRESS Wins 2017 HUGO AWARD|work=Newsarama|access-date=2017-08-15|language=en}}</ref>\n|[[Hugo Award for Best Graphic Story|Best Graphic Story]]\n|''Monstress \u2013 Volume 1: Awakening''\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2018<ref name=\"Hugos 2018\">{{Cite news|url= http://www.thehugoawards.org/2018/08/2018-hugo-award-winners/|title=2018 Hugo Award Winners|publisher=[[The Hugo Awards]]|accessdate=August 21, 2018}}</ref>\n|Best Graphic Story\n|''Monstress \u2013 Volume 2: The Blood''\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|Best Professional Artist\n|Sana Takeda\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|2019<ref name=\"Hugos 2019\">{{Cite news|url= http://www.thehugoawards.org/2019/08/2019-hugo-awards-announced/|title=2019 Hugo Award Winners|publisher=[[The Hugo Awards]]|accessdate=August 21, 2019}}</ref>\n|Best Graphic Story\n|''Monstress \u2013 Volume 3: Haven''\n|{{Won}}\n|}\n\n==Collected editions==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n! Title !! Material collected !! Publication date !! Format !! ISBN\n|-\n| ''Monstress \u2013 Volume 1: Awakening''<ref>{{cite web |title=Monstress, Vol. 1 TP |url=https://imagecomics.com/comics/releases/monstress-vol-1-tp}}</ref>|| ''Monstress'' #1\u20136 || July 13, 2016 || rowspan=4|Trade paperback || {{ISBNT| 9781632157096}}\n|-\n| ''Monstress \u2013 Volume 2: The Blood''<ref>{{cite web |title=Monstress, Vol. 2 TP |url=https://imagecomics.com/comics/releases/monstress-vol-2-tp}}</ref>|| ''Monstress'' #7\u201312 || July 5, 2017 || {{ISBNT| 9781534300415}}\n|-\n| ''Monstress \u2013 Volume 3: Haven''<ref>{{cite web |title=Monstress, Vol. 3 TP |url=https://imagecomics.com/comics/releases/monstress-vol-3-tp}}</ref>|| ''Monstress'' #13\u201318 || September 5, 2018 || {{ISBNT| 9781534306912}}\n|-\n| ''Monstress \u2013 Volume 4: The Chosen''<ref>{{cite web |title=Monstress, Vol. 4 TP |url=https://imagecomics.com/comics/releases/monstress-vol-4-tp}}</ref>|| ''Monstress'' #19\u201324 || September 25, 2019 || {{ISBNT| 9781534313361}}\n|-\n| ''Monstress \u2013 Book One<ref>{{cite web |title=Monstress, Book One HC|url=https://imagecomics.com/comics/releases/monstress-book-one-hc}}</ref>|| ''Monstress'' #1\u201318 || July 3, 2019 ||rowspan=1|Hardcover || {{ISBNT| 9781534312326}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website|https://www.imagecomics.com/comics/series/monstress}} at [[Image Comics]]\n{{Hugo Award for Best Graphic Story}}\n\n[[Category:2015 comics debuts]]\n[[Category:Feminist comics]]\n[[Category:Fantasy comics]]\n[[Category:Image Comics titles]]\n[[Category:Eisner Award winners for Best Continuing Series]]\n[[Category:Harvey Award winners]]\n[[Category:Hugo Award for Best Graphic Story-winning works]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Comics series by Marjorie Liu and Sana Takeda}}\n{{Infobox comic book title <!--Wikipedia:WikiProject Comics-->\n|title           = Monstress\n|image           = Monstress-01.png\n|caption         = ''Monstress'' #1 cover\n|schedule        = \n|ongoing=y\n|publisher       = [[Image Comics]]\n|date            = November 2015 \u2013 present\n|issues          = 26\n|genre           = Epic Fantasy\n|main_char_team  = Maika Halfwolf <br>Kippa<br>Master Ren<br>The Monster<br>Corvin D'Oro\n|writers         = [[Marjorie Liu]]\n|artists         = [[Sana Takeda]]\n|pencillers      = \n|inkers          = \n|letterers       = Rus Wooton\n|editors         = Jennifer M. Smith\n|creators        = [[Marjorie Liu]] & [[Sana Takeda]]\n|subcat          = Image Comics\n|sort            = Monstress (comic book)\n|TPB1            = '1.''' ''Awakening\n|ISBN1           = 9781632157096\n|TPB2            = '2.''' ''The Blood\n|ISBN2           = 9781534300415\n|TPB3            = '3.''' ''Haven\n|ISBN3           = 9781534306912\n|TPB4            = '4.''' ''The Chosen\n|ISBN4           = 9781534313361\n}}\n'''''Monstress''''' is an [[epic fantasy]] comics series written by [[Marjorie Liu]] and drawn by [[Sana Takeda]], published since 2015 by the American publisher [[Image Comics]].\n\nThe comic was described by the [[Los Angeles Review of Books]] as \"ambitious as [[George R. R. Martin]] or [[J. R. R. Tolkien]]\" for its high fantasy concepts and heavy world-building.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lareviewofbooks.org/article/monsters-come-home-marjorie-liu-sana-takedas-monstress/|title=Monsters Come Home: On Marjorie Liu and Sana Takeda\u2019s \u201cMonstress\u201d|last=Song|first=Min Hyoung|website=Los Angeles Review of Books|access-date=2019-05-13}}</ref> The series has earned many awards, including five [[Eisner Award|Eisner Awards]], four [[Hugo Award|Hugo Awards]], and the [[List of Harvey Award winners|Harvey Awards]] Book of the Year in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/newsbrief/index.html?record=2036|title=Publisher's Weekly|last=|first=|date=|website=www.publishersweekly.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref>\n\n== Summary ==\nThe series is set in a [[matriarchal]] world inspired by early 20th century Asia, and tells the story of Maika Halfwolf, a teenage girl who shares a mysterious psychic link with a powerful monster.<ref>{{cite web |title=Marjorie Liu |last1=Liu|first1=Marjorie|url=http://marjoriemliu.com/|accessdate=25 January 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Cruz\">{{cite news|last1=Cruz|first1=Lenika|title=Marjorie Liu on the Road to Making 'Monstress'|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2017/09/marjorie-liu-monstress-interview/539394/|accessdate=25 January 2018|work=The Atlantic}}</ref> The background to the story is a war between the Arcanics, magical creatures who sometimes can pass for human, and the Cumaea, an order of sorceresses who consume Arcanics to fuel their power. Maika is an Arcanic who looks human, and who is set on learning about and avenging her dead mother. Maika's left arm has been severed and a demon occasionally emerges from its stub.<ref name=\"JT\">{{cite news|last1=Kelts|first1=Roland|title=Breaking the comic book glass ceiling|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/culture/2017/03/18/general/breaking-comic-book-glass-ceiling/#.WmoQLLBG1aS|accessdate=25 January 2018|work=The Japan Times|date=19 March 2017}}[http://www.sanatakeda.com/17361773_10155153431077053_2235665766323301491_n.jpg image]</ref> The demon, who takes over her body and mind, is a source of great power, but challenging for Maika to understand and control.<ref name=\"Cruz\" /> \n\nLiu first introduced the story to Takeda in 2013. The two started working together a year later, and the first issue was published in November 2015; the trade paperback first volume in July 2016, the second in July 2017,<ref name=JT/> the third in September 2018,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://imagecomics.com/comics/releases/monstress-vol-3-tp|title=Monstress, Vol. 3 TP|website=Image Comics|language=en|access-date=2019-05-08}}</ref> and the fourth in September 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://imagecomics.com/comics/releases/monstress-vol-4-tp|title=Monstress, Vol. 4 TP|website=Image Comics|language=en|access-date=2019-11-20}}</ref>\n\n== Publication history ==\n[[Marjorie Liu|Liu]] has said that she struggled with depression before writing ''Monstress''. She had taken a hiatus from writing before returning to the industry with Image Comics.<ref name=TheAtlantic>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2017/09/marjorie-liu-monstress-interview/539394/|title=Marjorie Liu on the Road to Making 'Monstress'|last=Cruz|first=Lenika|date=2017-09-14|website=The Atlantic|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-13}}</ref>\n\nShe has described the comic as \"a huge epic fantasy.\" As such, the story required world-building. The first issue was triple-sized (70 pages) in order to properly introduce the various characters and factions.<ref name=TheAtlantic/>\n\nLiu and Takeda first worked together on Liu's run of ''[[X-23]]'' for [[Marvel Comics|Marvel]]. Liu would later describe her work with Takeda as \"a wonderful process; it felt like she was reading my mind.\" A native of Japan, Takeda's art takes inspiration from [[manga]].<ref name=TheAtlantic/>\n\n== Themes ==\n[[File:5.30.19MarjorieLiuByLuigiNovi51.jpg|thumb|left|Liu at a 2019 signing for ''Monstress'' #24 at [[Midtown Comics]] in Manhattan]]\nAccording to Liu, among the series's themes are the inner strength required to withstand constant dehumanization, as well as the power of friendship among women.<ref name=HollywoodReporter>{{cite news|last1=McMillan|first1=Graeme|title='Monstress': Inside The Fantasy Comic About Race, Feminism And The Monster Within|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/monstress-inside-fantasy-comic-race-836391|accessdate=24 November 2015|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=3 November 2015}}</ref> Race also plays a large role in the series. In the graphic novel the Arcanics, a race of magical creatures, have been at war with humans for decades, and they are now at a stalemate; however the humans are taking Arcanics and selling them as slaves to other humans.<ref name=HollywoodReporter/>\n\n== Reception ==\nThe first, triple-sized issue of ''Monstress'' received critical praise. Writing for ''[[Kotaku]]'', Evan Narcisse called it \"a gorgeous comic book about racism, war and slavery\", noting the intricate detail of Takeda's [[manga]]-inspired art.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Narcisse|first1=Evan|title=Monstress Is A Gorgeous Comic Book About Racism, War and Slavery|url=http://kotaku.com/monstress-is-a-gorgeous-comic-book-about-racism-war-an-1744178284|accessdate=24 November 2015|work=Kotaku|date=23 November 2015}}</ref> Reviewing the book for [[The A.V. Club]], Caitlin Rosberg described the leading characters, all women, as \"deeply flawed and showing layers of nuanced characterization that you don\u2019t often see in comic books\", and appreciated the series's \"sense of in-between-ness\u2014(...) neither traditionally Western nor manga, paced like a novel but drawn like a comic\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rosberg|first1=Caitlin|title=Monstress captivates with its fusion of Western comics and manga|url=http://www.avclub.com/article/monstress-captivates-its-fusion-western-comics-and-227787|accessdate=24 November 2015|work=A.V. Club|date=10 November 2015}}</ref>{{-}}\n\n===Awards===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n!Award\n!Year\n!Category\n!Nominee\n!Result\n|-\n|rowspan=3|[[British Fantasy Award]]\n|2017<ref name=\"BFA 2017\">{{cite web|title=Announcing the 2017 British Fantasy Award Winners|url=https://www.tor.com/2017/10/01/announcing-the-2017-british-fantasy-award-winners/|website=Tor|accessdate=April 29, 2018}}</ref>\n|Best Comic / Graphic Novel\n|''Monstress \u2013 Volume 1: Awakening''\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2018<ref name=\"BFA 2018\">{{cite web|title=British Fantasy Society, British Fantasy Awards 2018|url=http://www.britishfantasysociety.org/news/british-fantasy-society-british-fantasy-award-2018/|website=[[British Fantasy Society]]|accessdate=November 25, 2018}}</ref>\n|Best Comic / Graphic Novel\n|''Monstress \u2013 Volume 2: The Blood''\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|Best Artist\n|Sana Takeda\n|{{Nominated}}\n|-\n|rowspan=10|[[Eisner Awards]]\n|rowspan=2|2016<ref name=\"Eisners 2016\">{{cite web|title=2016 Eisner Award Winners (Full List)|url=https://www.newsarama.com/30298-2016-eisner-award-winners-full-list.html|website=Newsarama|accessdate=April 29, 2018}}</ref>\n|Best Writer\n|Marjorie Liu\n|{{Nominated}}\n|-\n|Best New Series\n|''Monstress''\n|{{Nominated}}\n|-\n|rowspan=3|2017<ref name=\"Eisners 2017\">{{cite web|title=2017 Eisner Awards Winners (Full List)|url=https://www.newsarama.com/35554-2017-eisner-award-winners-full-list.html|website=Newsarama|accessdate=April 29, 2018}}</ref>\n|Best Publication for Teens (ages 13\u201317)\n|''Monstress''\n|{{Nominated}}\n|-\n|Best Painter/Multimedia Artist (interior art)\n|Sana Takeda\n|{{Nominated}}\n|-\n|Best Cover Artist\n|Sana Takeda\n|{{Nominated}}\n|-\n|rowspan=5|2018<ref name=\"Eisners 2018\">{{cite web|title=2018 Eisner Awards Nominations|url=https://www.newsarama.com/39672-2018-eisner-awards-nominations.html|website=Newsarama|accessdate=April 29, 2018}}</ref>\n|Best Continuing Series\n|''Monstress''\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|Best Publication for Teens (ages 13\u201317)\n|''Monstress''\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|Best Writer\n|Marjorie Liu\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|Best Painter/Multimedia Artist (interior art)\n|Sana Takeda\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|Best Cover Artist\n|Sana Takeda\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|[[Harvey Awards]]\n|2018<ref name=\"Harveys 2018\">{{cite web|title=2018 Winners - The Harvey Awards|url=https://www.harveyawards.com/Winners/2018-Nominees/|website=[[Harvey Awards]]|accessdate=November 25, 2018}}</ref>\n|Book of the Year Award\n|''Monstress''\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|rowspan=4|[[Hugo Awards]]\n|2017<ref name=\"Hugos 2017\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newsarama.com/35915-2017-hugo-awards-winners.html|title=MONSTRESS Wins 2017 HUGO AWARD|work=Newsarama|access-date=2017-08-15|language=en}}</ref>\n|[[Hugo Award for Best Graphic Story|Best Graphic Story]]\n|''Monstress \u2013 Volume 1: Awakening''\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2018<ref name=\"Hugos 2018\">{{Cite news|url= http://www.thehugoawards.org/2018/08/2018-hugo-award-winners/|title=2018 Hugo Award Winners|publisher=[[The Hugo Awards]]|accessdate=August 21, 2018}}</ref>\n|Best Graphic Story\n|''Monstress \u2013 Volume 2: The Blood''\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|Best Professional Artist\n|Sana Takeda\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|2019<ref name=\"Hugos 2019\">{{Cite news|url= http://www.thehugoawards.org/2019/08/2019-hugo-awards-announced/|title=2019 Hugo Award Winners|publisher=[[The Hugo Awards]]|accessdate=August 21, 2019}}</ref>\n|Best Graphic Story\n|''Monstress \u2013 Volume 3: Haven''\n|{{Won}}\n|}\n\n==Collected editions==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n! Title !! Material collected !! Publication date !! Format !! ISBN\n|-\n| ''Monstress \u2013 Volume 1: Awakening''<ref>{{cite web |title=Monstress, Vol. 1 TP |url=https://imagecomics.com/comics/releases/monstress-vol-1-tp}}</ref>|| ''Monstress'' #1\u20136 || July 13, 2016 || rowspan=4|Trade paperback || {{ISBNT| 9781632157096}}\n|-\n| ''Monstress \u2013 Volume 2: The Blood''<ref>{{cite web |title=Monstress, Vol. 2 TP |url=https://imagecomics.com/comics/releases/monstress-vol-2-tp}}</ref>|| ''Monstress'' #7\u201312 || July 5, 2017 || {{ISBNT| 9781534300415}}\n|-\n| ''Monstress \u2013 Volume 3: Haven''<ref>{{cite web |title=Monstress, Vol. 3 TP |url=https://imagecomics.com/comics/releases/monstress-vol-3-tp}}</ref>|| ''Monstress'' #13\u201318 || September 5, 2018 || {{ISBNT| 9781534306912}}\n|-\n| ''Monstress \u2013 Volume 4: The Chosen''<ref>{{cite web |title=Monstress, Vol. 4 TP |url=https://imagecomics.com/comics/releases/monstress-vol-4-tp}}</ref>|| ''Monstress'' #19\u201324 || September 25, 2019 || {{ISBNT| 9781534313361}}\n|-\n| ''Monstress \u2013 Book One<ref>{{cite web |title=Monstress, Book One HC|url=https://imagecomics.com/comics/releases/monstress-book-one-hc}}</ref>|| ''Monstress'' #1\u201318 || July 3, 2019 ||rowspan=1|Hardcover || {{ISBNT| 9781534312326}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website|https://www.imagecomics.com/comics/series/monstress}} at [[Image Comics]]\n{{Hugo Award for Best Graphic Story}}\n\n[[Category:2015 comics debuts]]\n[[Category:Feminist comics]]\n[[Category:Fantasy comics]]\n[[Category:Image Comics titles]]\n[[Category:Eisner Award winners for Best Continuing Series]]\n[[Category:Harvey Award winners]]\n[[Category:Hugo Award for Best Graphic Story-winning works]]\n", "name_user": "Packer1028", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixed wording", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monstress_(comics)"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Singapore", "text_new": "{{short description|Ongoing COVID-19 viral pandemic in Singapore}}\n{{Current disaster|event=disease pandemic|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Singapore\n| map1            = COVID-19 Cases in Singapore by Planning Areas.svg\n| legend1         = {{center|Map of planning areas with confirmed (red) coronavirus cases (as of 9 April)}}\n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Singapore]]\n| first_case      = 23 January 2020\n| arrival_date    = 23 January 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=01|day1=23|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], China\n| recovery_cases  = 652<ref name=\"worldometers\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/ |title=worldometers.info |access-date=30 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129195657/https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/ |archive-date=29 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"DashBoard\"/><ref name=\"CTSG\"/>\n| deaths          = 10<ref name=\"worldometers\"/><ref name=\"DashBoard\">{{Cite web |url=https://coronaboard.com/ |title=COVID-19 Dashboard |access-date=5 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331135805/https://coronaboard.com/ |archive-date=31 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"CTSG\"/>\n| confirmed_cases = 3,699<ref name=\"worldometers\"/><ref name=\"DashBoard\"/><ref name=\"CTSG\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.coronatracker.com/country/sg |title=Corona Tracker Overview |access-date=30 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325143811/https://www.coronatracker.com/country/sg/ |archive-date=25 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>|Action taken: Circuit Breaker (7 Apr-4 May 2020)\nStatus: Enforcing (Expires: 4 May 2020; Tentative)\n| active          = \n| suspected_cases = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = {{url|https://www.moh.gov.sg/covid-19}}\n| First Case detected: = \n| Deaths from other causes = \n| Death from other causes = 1\n}}\nThe '''2020 coronavirus pandemic in Singapore''' is part of the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic|ongoing global pandemic]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19), a novel infectious disease caused by [[severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2]] (SARS-CoV-2).\n\nThe first case of COVID-19 was confirmed on 23 January.<ref name=\"Abdullah 2020\" /> To combat COVID-19, a multi-ministerial committee was formed on 22 January with Minister for National Development [[Lawrence Wong]] and Minister for Health [[Gan Kim Yong]] as the co-chairs and [[Prime Minister of Singapore|Prime Minister]] [[Lee Hsien Loong]] and [[Deputy Prime Minister of Singapore|Deputy Prime Minister]] and Minister for Finance [[Heng Swee Keat]] as advisors.<ref name=\"ST22Jan\" /><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.moh.gov.sg/docs/librariesprovider5/default-document-library/multi-ministry-taskforce-on-wuhan-coronavirus-and-tor---final.pdf |title=Multi-Ministry Taskforce on Wuhan Coronavirus:  Terms of Reference (TORs) and Composition |access-date=21 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321054236/https://www.moh.gov.sg/docs/librariesprovider5/default-document-library/multi-ministry-taskforce-on-wuhan-coronavirus-and-tor---final.pdf |archive-date=21 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 3 April, Singapore announced a stringent set of preventive measures which were collectively called 'circuit breaker'. This will be applied from 7 April to 4 May 2020.\n[[Singapore]] contributed US$500,000 to support [[WHO]] efforts against COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news |title=Singapore contributes US$500,000 to support WHO efforts against COVID-19 |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/singapore-contributes-s-500-000-to-support-who-covid-19-efforts-12568566 |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=CNA |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325020159/https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/singapore-contributes-s-500-000-to-support-who-covid-19-efforts-12568566 |archive-date=25 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/Singapore medical cases chart}}\n\n== Background ==\nOn 12 January 2020, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) confirmed that a [[novel coronavirus]] was the cause of a respiratory illness in a cluster of people in Wuhan City, Hubei Province, China, which was reported to the WHO on 31 December 2019.<ref name=Elsevier>{{cite web |url=https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center |title=Novel Coronavirus Information Center |last=Elsevier |date= |website=Elsevier Connect|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130171622/https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|archive-date=30 January 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Reynolds4March2020>{{Cite news |last=Reynolds |first=Matt |url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus |title=What is coronavirus and how close is it to becoming a pandemic? |date=4 March 2020 |work=Wired UK|access-date=5 March 2020 |issn=1357-0978|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305104806/https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus|archive-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Case fatality rate|case fatality ratio]] for COVID-19 has been much lower than [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS of 2003]],<ref name=Imperial13March2020>{{cite web |url= https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/ |title=Crunching the numbers for coronavirus |website=Imperial News|access-date=15 March 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200319084913/https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Gov.ukHCIDDef>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid |title=High consequence infectious diseases (HCID); Guidance and information about high consequence infectious diseases and their management in England |last= |first= |date= |website=GOV.UK |language=en|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200303051938/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid|archive-date=3 March 2020|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> but the [[Transmission (medicine)|transmission]] has been significantly greater, with a significant total death toll.<ref name=WFSA>{{cite web |url= https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus |title=World Federation Of Societies of Anaesthesiologists \u2013 Coronavirus |last= |first= |date= |website=www.wfsahq.org|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200312233527/https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus|archive-date=12 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Imperial13March2020/>\n\n== Statistics ==\nThe top plot shows the total number of cases as a function of time (by date) since 23 January 2020, the date of the first reported case in Singapore. The bottom plot shows the number of new cases as reported each day.\n{{Graph:Chart\n|type=line\n|linewidth=1\n|showSymbols=1\n|colors=orange, blue, red\n| legend=Legend\n| width = 900\n| height = 400\n| xAxisTitle = Date (day/month)\n| yAxisTitle = Total no. of cases (cumulative)\n| y1Title=Confirmed\n| y2Title=Recovered\n| y3Title=Deaths\n| xAxisAngle = -65\n| yGrid= |xGrid= \n| x =  23/1, 24/1, 25/1, 26/1, 27/1, 28/1, 29/1, 30/1, 31/1, 1/2, 2/2, 3/2, 4/2, 5/2, 6/2, 7/2, 8/2, 9/2, 10/2, 11/2, 12/2, 13/2, 14/2, 15/2, 16/2, 17/2, 18/2, 19/2, 20/2, 21/2, 22/2, 23/2, 24/2, 25/2, 26/2, 27/2, 28/2, 29/2, 1/3, 2/3, 3/3, 4/3, 5/3, 6/3, 7/3, 8/3, 9/3, 10/3, 11/3, 12/3, 13/3, 14/3, 15/3, 16/3, 17/3, 18/3, 19/3, 20/3, 21/3, 22/3, 23/3, 24/3, 25/3, 26/3, 27/3, 28/3, 29/3, 30/3, 31/3, 1/4, 2/4, 3/4, 4/4, 5/4, 6/4, 7/4, 8/4, 9/4, 1