nsonby Defeat Athletics/Closely Contested Game\n| page =5\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LIX| issue=18210\n| date = 1922-09-02\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19221002.2.19.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-29}}</ref>| away = Athletics\n| try1 = [[Thomas McClymont]] 2, McNeil\n| con1 = [[Thomas McClymont]]\n| pen1 =\n| try2 = Nicholson, [[Eric Grey]]\n| con2 = [[Eric Grey]]\n| pen2 = [[Eric Grey]]\n| stadium = Carlaw Park 1\n| attendance =\n| referee = Bert Gallagher\n}}\n\n==Top Try Scorers and Point Scorers==\nThese lists include tries and points scored in the First Grade competition and the Roope Rooster competition only. Ben Davidson set a record for the number of points scored by a single player in a season. While earlier seasons were often incomplete with some points unattributed his 116 points was well ahead of the previous highest of 78 by [[Karl Ifwersen]] in the [[1915 Auckland Rugby League season|1915 season]]. P Gallagher of Marist was the top try scorer with 15.\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!Rank!!Player!!Team!!Tries\n|-\n|1||P Gallagher||Marist Old Boys||15\n|-\n|2||[[Ben Davidson (rugby league)|Ben Davidson]]||City Rovers||12\n|-\n|3||[[George Davidson (athlete)|George Davidson]]||City Rovers||10\n|-\n|3||[[Eric Grey]]||Athletic||10\n|-\n|5||[[Bert Avery]]||Athletic||9\n|-\n|6||[[Bill Davidson (rugby league)|Bill Davidson]]||City Rovers||8\n|-\n|6||G Yardley||Athletic||8\n|-\n|6||[[Maurice Wetherill]]||City Rovers||8\n|-\n|6||[[Ivan Littlewood]]||Ponsonby United||8\n|-\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!Rank!!Player!!Team!!Tries!!Con!!Pen!!Mark!!Drop Goal!!Points\n|-\n|1||[[Bill Davidson (rugby league)|Bill Davidson]]||City Rovers||8||33||13||0||0||116\n|-\n|2||[[Eric Grey]]||Athletic||10||10||4||1||5||70\n|-\n|3||[[Thomas McClymont]]||Ponsonby United||6||18||1||0||0||56\n|-\n|4||Wareing||Fire Brigade||7||6||11||0||0||55\n|-\n|5||[[Clarrie Polson]]||Newton Rangers||5||12||4||0||0||47\n|-\n|5||P Gallagher||Marist Old Boys||15||1||0||0||0||47\n|-\n|7||[[Ben Davidson (rugby league)|Ben Davidson]]||City Rovers||12||1||0||0||1||40\n|-\n|7||G Yardley||Athletic||8||5||3||0||0||40\n|-\n|9||[[Maurice Wetherill]]||City Rovers||8||5||2||0||0||38\n|-\n|10||[[Frank Delgrosso]]||Ponsonby United||7||3||5||0||0||37\n|-\n|10||[[Craddock Dufty]]||Athletic||3||9||5||0||0||37\n|-\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n== Challenge Shield Matches ==\n[[City Rovers]] came into the season as holders of the trophy after defeating Ponsonby United the previous season. The shield had taken the place of the Thacker Shield which had been taken from Ponsonby and returned to the Canterbury Rugby League after a dispute over who was eligible to compete for it. City went on to defend the shield 3 times during the season defeating Petone, Tongariro, and Huntly.\n\n===City v Petone===\n{{rugbybox collapsible\n| date = 7 October\n| time = 3:00\n| home = City\n| score = 5\u20133\n| report = <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Challenge Shield Match\n| page =4\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LIX| issue=18216\n| date = 1922-10-09\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19221009.2.12.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-29}}</ref>\n| away = Petone\n| try1 = Wilson\n| con1 =\n| pen1 = Crowther\n| try2 = Kruse\n| con2 =\n| pen2 =\n| stadium = Carlaw Park\n| attendance =\n| referee = Archie Ferguson\n}}\n\n===City v Tongariro===\nThe Tongariro team was \u201cmade up of Maori players drawn from the scattered settlements of the King Country\u201d according to the New Zealand Herald match report, though were missing some of their best players. The Auckland Star reported that many of their players were graduates of Te Aute College.\n{{rugbybox collapsible\n| date = 14 October\n| time = 3:00\n| home = City\n| score = 37\u201314\n| report = <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Challenge Shield Match/City Defeats Tongariro/Fast and Exciting Game\n| page =5\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LIX| issue=18222\n| date = 1922-10-16\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19221016.2.23.1\n| accessdate = 2020-03-11}}</ref>\n| away = Tongariro\n| try1 = [[Maurice Wetherill]] 3, [[Alf Townsend]], E Mackie, [[George Paki]], F Wilson, [[Ben Davidson (rugby league)|Ben Davidson]] 2\n| con1 = E Mackie 3, H Hawkes\n| pen1 = S Crowther\n| try2 = Springall, H Pau, Taia, Hamu\n| con2 = H Pau\n| pen2 =\n| stadium = Carlaw Park 1\n| attendance =\n| referee = L Bull\n}}\n\n===City v Huntly===\nHuntly came to Auckland as the South Auckland (Waikato) champions and were expected to provide a stern test to City however after a competitive first half they fell away badly in the second half with City ending up running in 11 tries.\n{{rugbybox collapsible\n| date = 28 October\n| time = 3:00\n| home = City\n| score = 43\u201313\n| report = <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Challenge Shield Match/City Defeats Huntly/Fast Play by Local Backs\n| page = 4\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LIX| issue=18234\n| date = 1922-10-30\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19221030.2.7.1\n| accessdate = 2020-03-11}}</ref>\n| away = Huntly\n| try1 = H Hawkes 4, [[Maurice Wetherill]], [[Ben Davidson (rugby league)|Ben Davidson]] 3, [[George Davidson (athlete)|George Davidson]] 2, [[George Paki]]\n| con1 = H Hawkes, [[Maurice Wetherill]], [[George Davidson (athlete)|George Davidson]], E Mackie, [[George Paki]]\n| pen1 =\n| try2 = S Raynor, Sheeran, Peckham\n| con2 =\n| pen2 = G Raynor 2\n| stadium = Carlaw Park 1\n| attendance =\n| referee =\n}}\n\n== Lower Grades ==\n=== Lower Grade Clubs ===\nThere were 6 lower grades in 1922 if you include the Sixth Grade which was split into an A and B grade.\n\nGrades were made of the following teams with the winning team in bold:\n*'''Second Grade''': Athletics, '''City''', Devonport United, Ihumatao (misspelt as 'Ihumata' in the Newspapers), Mangere, Manukau, Newton, Northcote, Otahuhu, Ponsonby, Richmond, (City defeated Devonport 16\u201313 in the final).\n*'''Third Grade Myers Cup''': Athletics, City A, City B, Coromandel, Devonport, Ellerslie, Kingsland, Manukau, Newton, Northcote, Parnell, Point Chevalier, '''Ponsonby''' (undefeated), and Richmond.\n*'''Fourth Grade''': Athletics, City, Devonport United, Ellerslie, Newton, Otahuhu, Parnell, Ponsonby, and '''Richmond'''.\n*'''Fifth Grade Endean Memorial Shield''': Devonport, Marist Old Boys, Marist Old Boys, Manukau, Newton, Northcote, Ponsonby, Richmond, and '''Takapuna'''.\n*'''Sixth Grade A''': '''City''', Athletics A, Athletics B, Ellerslie, Kingsland, Manukau A, Manukau B, Northcote, Otahuhu, Parnell, Ponsonby, Richmond\n*'''Sixth Grade B''': '''Athletics''', City, Manukau, Marist Old Boys, Northcote, Parnell, Richmond\n*'''Cadet Competition''': Athletic Cadets, '''22nd (Eden) Company''', 26th Company, 29th Company, 36th (Northcote) Company\n\n== Representative Season ==\nIt was an extremely busy season for the Auckland representative side. They played ten matches in total, while many members of the side also played for the Auckland Provincial team, and an Auckland B team also played a match in Cambridge. Of the ten matches they lost 6 and won 4. The first representative fixture of the season was played on 20 May between Auckland and the Maori team which was preparing to visit Australia and play a series of matches. There were 7,000 in attendance and gate receipts totaled \u00a3297 2s 6d. On 19 June the touring Australian Universities Rugby League team arrived in [[Auckland]] on board the \u2018Manuka\u2019. They were welcomed at a function at the [[Auckland Town Hall]] by a large assembly of Auckland politicians including the Mayor Mr. [[James Gunson|J.H. Gunson]], and representatives of Auckland Rugby League and the New Zealand League Council.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Visiting Footballers/Team From Australia/Civic Welcome Tendered/Members\u2019 Amateur Status\n| page =9\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LIX| issue=18122\n| date = 1922-06-21\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19220621.2.123| accessdate = 2019-08-26}}</ref> The Australians acquitted themselves well by beating Auckland twice, and losing to them once and a loss to the South Waikato team in [[Hamilton, New Zealand|Hamilton]]. The games were played over the space of just 8 days.\n\nAfter the [[New Zealand M\u0101ori rugby league team|NZ M\u0101ori]] team returned from their tour of Australia seven members of their team were transferred to the Fire Brigade Club, though only four played in their round 9 match (Pitman, Gardner, Yeats and Te Whata).\n\nHistory was made on 2 September when [[Auckland rugby league team|Auckland]] was defeated for the first time in a Northern Union Challenge Cup match. They had held the Cup for over a decade, but had to hand it over when they were defeated by [[Waikato rugby league team|South Auckland]] 21 to 20 on [[Carlaw Park]] in front of a large crowd. On 16 September they met the touring New South Wales team at the [[Auckland Domain]] and in front of a huge crowd of 20,000 they went down in a \u201ctremendously fast and exciting game\u201d by 45 points to 25.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =New South Wales Team\n| page =9\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LIX| issue=18198\n| date = 1922-09-20\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19220918.2.111\n| accessdate = 2019-08-29}}</ref>\n\n===Auckland v New Zealand Maori===\n{{rugbybox collapsible\n| date = 20 May\n| time = 3:00\n| home = Auckland\n| score = 18\u201328\n| report = <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Maori\u2019s Play Well/Defeat of Auckland/28 Points to Eighteen/Fast and Exciting Game/Visitors Show Great Dash\n| page =9\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LIX| issue=18096\n| date = 1922-05-22\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19220522.2.121\n| accessdate = 2019-08-27}}</ref>\n| away = New Zealand Maori\n| try1 = [[John Lang (New Zealand rugby league)|John Lang]] 2, [[Clarrie Polson]], [[Maurice Wetherill]]\n| con1 = [[Bill Davidson (rugby league)|Bill Davidson]] 3\n| pen1 =\n| try2 = Yates, Morrison, [[Craddock Dufty]], Lockwood 2, Whata\n| con2 = [[Craddock Dufty]] 2, Whata\n| pen2 = [[Craddock Dufty]], Yates\n| stadium = Carlaw Park 1\n| attendance = 7000\n| referee = W Murray\n}}\n\n===Auckland v Australian Universities===\nThe Australian University team was made up of players from Sydney University and Brisbane University.\n{{rugbybox collapsible\n| date = 21 June\n| time = 3:00\n| home = Auckland\n| score = 12\u201313\n| report = <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Australian University V Auckland/Visitors Win By a Point\n| page =8\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LIII| issue=146\n| date = 1922-06-22\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19220622.2.105\n| accessdate = 2019-08-27}}</ref>\n| away = Australian Universities\n| try1 = [[Ivan Littlewood]], [[Nelson Bass]]\n| con1 = [[Bill Davidson (rugby league)|Bill Davidson]]\n| pen1 = [[Bill Davidson (rugby league)|Bill Davidson]], [[Thomas McClymont]]\n| try2 = WP Lynskey, F Cripps, J Dunworth\n| con2 = H Courtenay\n| pen2 = J Craig\n| stadium = Carlaw Park 1\n| attendance =\n| referee = W Murray\n}}\n\n===Auckland v Australian Universities===\n{{rugbybox collapsible\n| date = 24 June\n| time = 3:00\n| home = Auckland\n| score = 7\u201318\n| report = <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Universities V Auckland/Australians\u2019 Second Win/Good Game at Domain\n| page =9\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LIX| issue=18126\n| date = 1922-06-22\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19220626.2.105\n| accessdate = 2019-08-27}}</ref>| away = Australian Universities\n| try1 = [[Nelson Bass]]\n| con1 =\n| pen1 = [[Bill Davidson (rugby league)|Bill Davidson]], [[Arthur Singe]]\n| try2 = J Craig, Cunningham, Cripps\n| con2 = J Craig, Courtney\n| pen2 =\n| stadium = Auckland Domain\n| attendance = 12-150